-- Cotton Prices Jump to Highest in 11 Months: Commodities at Close
-- B y   T h o m a s   G a l a t o l a
-- 2013-03-15T21:00:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-15/cotton-prices-jump-to-highest-in-11-months-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot
Index of 24  raw materials  rose 0.3 percent to settle at 652.5 at
3:44 p.m.  New York  time, led by cotton.  The UBS Bloomberg CMCI gauge of 26  prices  gained less than
0.1 percent to 1,551.45.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cotton futures jumped to the highest in 11 months on
speculation that  China , the world’s biggest consumer, will
increase imports.  The  U.S. Department of Agriculture  last week raised its
estimate for Chinese consumption this year to 36 million bales,
up by 1.4 percent from a month earlier. The USDA also boosted
its forecast for the Asian nation’s imports by 7.1 percent.  On ICE Futures U.S. in New York, cotton for May delivery
advanced 1.8 percent to 92.5 cents a pound. Earlier, the price
reached 93.93 cents, the highest for a most-active contract
since March 30, 2012.  Raw-sugar futures for May delivery rose 0.3 percent to
18.89 cents a pound.  Orange-juice futures for May delivery climbed 1.6 percent
to $1.392 a pound.  Arabica-coffee futures for delivery in May fell 1.5 percent
to $1.375 a pound, the fifth straight drop and the longest slump
since Aug. 16. Earlier, the price touched $1.3715, the lowest
since June 10, 2010.  Cocoa futures for May delivery fell 0.7 percent to $2,115 a
metric ton.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas jumped to a 16-week high on speculation that a
late cold blast heading into the U.S. spring will boost heating
demand.  On the  New York Mercantile Exchange , gas futures for April
delivery rose 1.6 percent to $3.872 per million British thermal
units, the highest settlement since Nov. 23. This week, the
price climbed 6.7 percent, the most in two months.  U.K. same-day gas dropped as much as 6.8% to 72 pence a
therm, and was at 74.5 pence at 5:27 p.m. in London, according
to broker prices compiled by Bloomberg. A therm is 100,000 Btu.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold futures rose, capping the biggest weekly gain in two
months, as demand improves for the metal as an inflation hedge,
including by retail buyers of coins, bars and jewelry.  On the Comex in New York, gold futures for April delivery
added 0.1 percent to $1,592.60 an ounce, extending the weekly
gain to 1 percent, the most since Jan. 18.  Silver futures for May delivery advanced 0.2 percent to
$28.851 an ounce.  On the Nymex, platinum futures for April delivery gained
0.2 percent to $1,592.40 an ounce.  Palladium futures for June delivery jumped 0.6 percent to
$775.65 an ounce.  CRUDE OIL  Crude oil gained for the sixth time in seven sessions as
the dollar weakened and inventories fell at a major storage hub.  On the Nymex, oil futures for April delivery rose 0.5
percent to $93.45 a barrel.  Brent oil for May delivery climbed 0.8 percent to $109.82 a
barrel on the London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange.  BP Plc bought a cargo of North Sea Forties crude at the
highest in two weeks. There were no trades for Russian Urals
grade.  Exports of Azeri Light from  Georgia ’s Black Sea port of
Supsa in April will be four cargoes, according to two traders
with knowledge of the loading plan.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline rose for the first time this week after U.S.
economic data signaled improvement in demand.  On the Nymex, gasoline futures for April delivery increased
0.7 percent to $3.1638 a gallon.  Heating-oil futures for April delivery gained 0.3 percent
to $2.939 a gallon  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Soybean futures fell, capping the longest slump in a month,
on speculation that a quickening harvest in  Brazil  will erode
demand for U.S. exports.  On the Chicago Board of Trade, soybean futures for May
delivery fell 0.7 percent to $14.26 a bushel. The price dropped
for the fourth straight day, the longest slump since Feb. 12.  Wheat futures for May delivery dropped 0.2 percent to $7.23
a bushel.  Corn futures for May delivery rose 0.1 percent to $7.17 a
bushel.  BASE METALS  Copper prices fell for the second time in three days as
confidence among American consumers unexpectedly slumped in
March.  On the Comex, copper futures for May delivery dropped 0.5
percent to $3.5205 a pound, leaving prices down 3.6 percent this
year.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months declined 0.6 percent to $7,752 a ton ($3.52 a pound).
Aluminum, nickel, zinc, tin and lead prices also fell.  LIVESTOCK  Cattle futures declined to the lowest since July as U.S.
meat processors slowed purchases on signs of weakening demand
for beef.  On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, cattle futures for June
delivery fell 1.5 percent to $1.213 a pound, after touching
$1.212, the lowest for the most-active contract since July 18.  Feeder-cattle futures for May settlement dropped 1.6
percent to $1.41075 a pound.  Hog futures for June settlement retreated 1.3 percent to
89.325 cents a pound.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Thomas Galatola in New York at 
